<page_title>How water molecules are produced from hydrogen and oxygen molecules</page_title>
<bg_color><Red>255</Red><Green>255</Green><Blue>204</Blue></bg_color>
<text>Experimental evidences[1] suggest that water molecules may form from hydrogen and oxygen through the following elementary steps:

  

The primary chain reaction in the H2O reaction. The dashed lines represent paths to the premature chain termination. The solid circles represent electrons, and the open circles represent holes. For an explanation of what holes are, see the caption of the first figure on this page.

Unlike the A2 + B2 &#8594; 2AB reaction where one free radical produces exactly one free radical in a loop, in this reaction, one hydrogen free radical produces three free radicals: two OH and another H! Therefore, this reaction is expected to be explosive once started, because the heat energy released from the exothermic steps will accelerate the diffusion of free radicals and their number will grow exponentially in the initial phase (with a growth coefficient equal to 3!). This is probably one of the reasons why liquid hydrogen and oxygen are used as rocket fuel.

  
    
This is a non-explosive reaction. Click here to see a note about the reaction rates.

Parameter settings: The blue atoms represent oxygen atoms and the green ones hydrogen atoms. The atomic radius of O is set to be 0.75 angstrom and that of H is set to be 0.5 angstrom (not exactly their experimental values). The masses of the O and H atom are set to be 16 g/mol and 1 g/mol, respectively. The dissociation energies for H-H, O=O and O-H are set to be 104, 119 and 120 kcal/mol, respectively. The bond-exchange potential barriers for the elementary reactions are unknown, so we set it to be very small (0.23 kcal/mol) to accelerate the reaction.

Instruction:  The reaction in the above model is not explosive because we have applied a heat bath to remove the energy evolved from the reaction. Click here to view the simulation of an explosive reaction.

The chain-termination step in this reaction worths some thinking, as you may have found that this step actually does happen with a noticeable frequency than that of the chain-termination step in the A2+B2 &#8594; 2AB reaction. How does it come to this? The secret lies in the O+H2 &#8594; OH+H step. This elementary reaction produces two free radicals, one OH and one H, but when the step ends, the two radicals are not actually far away from each other. There is a significant probability that these two radicals, due to frequent random collisions, might rotate, meet and react shortly after they are produced. When they do react, the overall reaction slows down. The reaction, therefore, may not go as fast as it can when there are a lot of chain termination reactions occuring. This may help explain why this reaction can be turned non-explosive by changing pressure.
</text>
